skos:ConceptScheme.dcterms:title: {"id": "148b929a-fee0-4cab-acf8-78a855c19282", "value": "Building Materials (CAAL)"}
skos:ConceptScheme.dcterms:description: {"id": "1fdd10b1-4475-4f7c-91cf-e06288a38e21", "value": "Thesaurus of main constructional material types (eg. the walls) for indexing of monuments."}

skos:Concept.skos:scopeNote: {"id": "e975e065-179b-4f6f-9ebf-d7b78311ace7", "value": "Coarse grained, metamorphic rock in which the colour is dependent upon the predominant mineral."}

{"id": "e1210cce-2b5f-4d1d-aeae-5b9138debea3", "value": "Standard rectangular block or tablet bonded on mortar joints in a regular arrangement or pattern for strength or decoration. Made from clay or brick earth which may contain varying quantities of chalk, lime or iron oxide which effect colour or density."}
{"id": "705f9134-1511-4f16-b801-361aed153448", "value": "A fine grained earth which becomes more plastic when water is added and can be moulded and dried to make bricks, tile, pottery, etc."}
{"id": "93494be6-b95b-44a2-b325-f255e8581472", "value": "Medium grained, hard, white/grey coloured stone consisting of quartz and often silica, produced by the metamorphosis of sandstone."}

{"id": "8646c5cd-989f-43b1-8855-6ee19b8fad9d", "value": "Hard, transparent, often coloured mineral. Can be found on its own as crystals and veins but also as a major constituent of rocks such as granite. Often used decoratively."}
{"id": "21a688c9-b17b-4018-8da3-3b2b56c82743", "value": "Plaster which has been painted either for decorative purposes or to protect it."}

{"id": "a2ef7657-80c8-4e12-bec6-6ee288a7c4b0", "value": "Wooden roof tile (traditionally oak) which is riven or sawn from good quality timber to a regular size and used as a roof and/or wall covering. Index with type of wood if known."}
{"id": "5b4d2533-2e20-4599-8535-03f001a25885", "value": "Wood, cut and seasoned so forming or capable of forming any part of a structure. May be treated with preservative before use."}

{"id": "fa98f778-3829-4082-81d1-0d9a15b6cc13", "value": "Wooden rods or stakes which can be interlaced with twigs or branches to make walls or fences, or more commonly, to form the basis of panels in traditional timber framed buildings which are then covered with daub."}
{"id": "bb7a3bf9-720c-4aee-af6d-1d057f3dca6b", "value": "Hard, compact, unprocessed, fibrous cellulose substance. The roots, trunks and branches of trees and shrubs consist of this tissue."}
{"id": "9177d707-6025-4c2a-9255-7d8b0fb31f91", "value": "Animal skin that has been hardened or treated by a tanning process."}
{"id": "6e9b2398-e4be-4e7b-a92d-a6f7335b60b0", "value": "A native hardwood of the Beech family with hard and durable characteristics which traditionally made it appropriate for structural work."}
{"id": "219bc77b-92f2-41ef-af22-f2bdd248f240", "value": "Thin flexible sheets made from the pulp of wood or other fibrous matter."}
{"id": "40b303aa-be02-4510-b1b2-0b6142e4a181", "value": "Basic, black coloured, fine grained, igneous rock."}

{"id": "43988fcc-e772-4654-be3b-5125ea04bd27", "value": "Medium to coarse grained, green to dark red/black coloured igneous rock, mainly found on The Lizard, South West Cornwall. Due to its fragmentary structure, Serpentine is mainly used for decorative and ornamental purposes."}

{"id": "001baadb-15fa-4834-9f18-a00108dc5a39", "value": "Metal used primarily for roof coverings and window fittings. It is easy to work, can be worked cold and does not rust which makes it suitable for holding or repelling water."}

{"id": "82048f72-ea75-4278-847b-9a26fa7eacbb", "value": "The oldest form of iron, it is a tough, pure form of iron that can be fashioned into decorative items or shapes by hammering, squeezing or rolling."}

{"id": "25407cc4-982e-416c-9bb4-16383f351606", "value": "Smooth rendering applied to the exterior of buildings which may be incised to suggest coursed masonry. Made of lime and sand or brick dust, and more recently, cement."}
{"id": "000129c0-4cc1-446c-947d-f64e30c7a957", "value": "Soft mineral, colour varying from black/purple to yellow/green. Commonly found as a mineral vein."}

{"id": "451824e4-3ce2-4910-96ec-ec2293beb754", "value": "Soft, often white, but may be transparent. Dolomite can be found on its own, but may also occur as a replacement mineral found in some rocks, particularly limestone, formed after action by magnesium-rich fluids."}
{"id": "3a638e72-e98d-4da9-93d1-84567407e627", "value": "Medium hard, green/black coloured. Found in many igneous and metamorphic rocks."}
{"id": "22fddbda-499d-4b20-9c71-bc5d0d899ff9", "value": "Natural inorganic substance possessing a definite chemical composition in a crystalline form. See MINERAL Class Listnfor narrow terms."}

{"id": "f1075783-78f7-44da-945a-b6ca56bf2142", "value": "Hard, often coloured, can be transparent. Found on its own as crystals and veins but also as a major constituent of all three geological rock types."}
{"id": "212b6abf-3b3c-4408-a018-f738dbe2581d", "value": "Easily formed metal alloy composed of copper and zinc."}
{"id": "29e7275a-5f71-4348-b8ff-6ea51d49a9b0", "value": "A hard and lustrous metallic element, used for roofing, galvanising iron and a component of alloys such as brass."}
{"id": "e4b00233-91cf-40bb-a003-2e506d6f46b8", "value": "A malleable, ductile ferromagnetic metal widely used for structural and decorative purposes."}
{"id": "06af92c5-533b-4d24-babb-a0a8bcc4d5b2", "value": "A precious metal of lustrous white colour with great malleability and ductility."}
{"id": "945afed9-c288-4350-bd49-396938442d2a", "value": "Hard, corrosive resistant alloy of copper and tin."}

{"id": "febce2d0-a5f8-434c-933e-368eddf5f2a3", "value": "An alloy of iron and carbon, its strength makes it suitable for load bearing purposes. It is primarily used in structural steelwork and concrete reinforcement."}

{"id": "7e3014aa-2479-42bf-88de-5ba22c574bc4", "value": "Class of elements and alloys that are characteristically lustrous,ductile, fusible and malleable. These are extracted from ore minerals originally existing in nature and processed before becoming a recognisable metal. See METAL Class List for narrow terms"}
{"id": "0abd2ebd-4ff3-4fe0-81d5-6b0de3fa74cb", "value": "A precious metal characterised by its yellow colour and resistance to tarnishing."}
{"id": "8850b78b-6741-4675-a7b2-9ccfb95e4a8e", "value": "Malleable metal used for roofing and for alloys such as bronze."}
{"id": "a489c630-1eeb-4d00-9b0f-1e648ac9a655", "value": "Metal used primarily for roofing and ornamental purposes, being lighter and stronger than lead."}
{"id": "2e4a8b88-4cc5-4fde-a0b7-37c08b5fba75", "value": "Lightweight, strong metal with good corrosive resistance, normally used as an alloy."}
{"id": "62426837-2bd9-403c-879f-b42e40cbf8bd", "value": "Designating or pertaining to hard, brittle substances produced by strong heating of clay."}
{"id": "1121956f-c0c5-4cfa-8e07-a586b58feb47", "value": "Sedimentary rock consisting of rounded pebbles naturally cemented together."}
{"id": "b53e0f7a-d9ea-47b8-b52b-7577c18acd02", "value": "Medium grained, intrusive, black or dark green coloured, igneous rock."}
{"id": "c5ec4737-3942-41a6-b2be-4bbea7dc93d0", "value": "Ornate or patterned decoration, carved into or moulded from plaster."}
{"id": "82fe8f91-316f-40e9-9d92-8911cff20eaa", "value": "Squared block of glass, tile, stone or marble used in mosaic."}
{"id": "53b29f48-2c46-41bd-8eeb-1eb470c950a4", "value": "Grains of rock fragment larger than coarse sand and finer than pebbles (diameter 2-4mm)."}
{"id": "8438b962-92a9-4aea-8961-2627895bdf17", "value": "Tablet of a uniform shape. Used as finishing or covering materials which fit together in a regular format."}

{"id": "f7fa1ea8-3fdf-4401-9c5e-5620781f0351", "value": "A raw material determined by its form or a finished product material characterised by its end shape or form. See MATERIAL <BY FORM> Class List for narrow terms."}
{"id": "77ea838d-b227-4ae1-9bbd-8d88b827e9d2", "value": "A square, hewn or worked, high class freestone which can be 'freely' cut and is laid in horizontal courses with vertical joints."}
{"id": "20a99390-2ee9-435a-b5ed-c6e30c558356", "value": "Rock fragment (diameter 4-64mm) larger than gravel and smaller than cobble, combined with other material e.g. flint, for decorative effect."}
{"id": "060fc759-e294-4327-b9c3-798a49c69a32", "value": "Naturally occurring glacial rock fragments (diameter 64-256mm) larger than pebble and smaller than boulder."}
{"id": "84c7dfa5-2ab4-47c1-88b7-ebfb6dfc6e10", "value": "Rough, unhewn, undressed building stones with irregular faces, generally not laid in regular courses. Index with type of stone if specified."}

{"id": "dda23554-7534-4cff-a8fa-ec4bff07132d", "value": "Traditional roof covering consisting of materials such as reed, straw or heather layered and fastened together onto roof to form a run off to prevent water penetration."}

{"id": "2950091c-cc1b-4856-b92c-84c51c5fc7fe", "value": "Deciduous wood from the native elm tree, commonly used for framing or cladding of lesser timber framed structures due to its poorer weathering qualities as compared to oak."}
{"id": "9169d417-04bf-43bd-b12a-923127bc60dd", "value": "Any of the pieces of hard tissue consisting largely of calcium phosphate that make up the skeleton of a vertebrate animal."}
{"id": "5c154c10-932e-4263-a280-08b1f1acf1d4", "value": "Sedimentary rock consisting mainly of calcium carbonate. Varying in grain size, colour and hardness."}
{"id": "de6f3b72-d7fa-40d8-b73d-2489a74a0bf6", "value": "Collective name for, in a true geological sense, a metamorphosed limestone, eg. Carrara marble."}
{"id": "763f65c5-2112-4a8c-8c9e-eb4f446522ac", "value": "Fine grained, whitish, granular variety of Gypsum. Suitable for carving."}

{"id": "d35127eb-21ee-42bc-9fd7-eff62468cb23", "value": "Geologically sandstone consists of particles of quartz naturally cemented together by either silica, calcium or iron. It is this geological composition that accounts for the varying colours and grain sizes found in the many building sandstones."}
{"id": "2ccc9f71-e2e1-4ad5-acf3-9812f1f1a243", "value": "Collective name for any stone that has become impregnated with iron oxide."}
{"id": "65933c81-670d-4f93-9785-657f3b5e25dd", "value": "Soft, very fine grained, dark coloured, sedimentary rock which splits easily."}
{"id": "29d1af97-0aa9-4cac-a2b3-d358397c9dbf", "value": "Fine grained, yellow/buff to grey/black coloured sedimentary rock."}
{"id": "3acca59d-f21f-4c5c-9242-f969324a73f7", "value": "Rock of definite form and size, usually artificially shaped. See STONE CLass List for narrow terms."}
{"id": "1c8ed356-6f98-41f6-9270-ffa7bb7feeba", "value": "A hard, coarse grained, durable igneous rock. Can be used decoratively or as a main material."}
{"id": "3d017c7e-36d4-46da-92f5-bd55e394d141", "value": "A hard, silica rich rock, black or brown coloured, commonly found in nodular form."}
{"id": "afc110b0-e777-4db1-842c-1685dece6d87", "value": "Medium to coarse grained metamorphic rock, colour being determined by its dominant mineral. Often used for floor and wall cladding."}

{"id": "32b0ddff-9de0-4a45-97d6-93469516d01b", "value": "Collective term for a hard, fine grained, dark coloured metamorphic rock, which splits easily; hence its common use as a roofing and flooring material, and a functional description for any rectangular, sheet, roofing material."}
{"id": "42e62d32-9195-435b-8bc5-cf3eecff23ca", "value": "Traditional term for any fine to medium grained igneous rock, containing large crystal fragments."}
{"id": "d506a7d3-fe43-42be-8f25-d1b00e5d4e8d", "value": "Coarse grained, dark coloured, igneous rock."}
{"id": "c2f648de-3aed-43f9-8f78-de794f5eb8cf", "value": "A light porous cellular rock, consisting of consolidated volcanic ash ejected from vents during a volcanic eruption."}

{"id": "9ddd9fe5-00f6-432d-b657-a4f048ef07de", "value": "Lime plaster, consisting of lime and sand, is the oldest type of render. Applied externally to walls or onto laths for infill panels and usually limewashed."}

{"id": "bcf1da34-4b0f-4e0c-8ae2-0a9f53e7763a", "value": "Calcium Oxide obtained by heating limestone in a kiln. Used as a constituent of modern mortar, or as slaked (non-hydraulic) lime in lime putty, daub, limewash and traditional lime plaster, mortar and renders."}

{"id": "fbbb1c88-ce79-4bda-a205-72f144cbf480", "value": "Application of earth based plaster to a backing of lath or wattle used in internal or external walls. Composite mixture which may include clay soil, dung, straw, lime putty, sand or horsehair."}
{"id": "6b9baf8d-d8f4-4abb-a020-cd483db72f2c", "value": "A general term for the weatherproof coat on the external walls of a building."}

{"id": "863f5f6e-2fc6-4d7e-96ea-8a441ec9ab62", "value": "Originally obtained by burning limestone to produce quicklime. Now a fine grey powder made from a mixture of limestone and clay used with water and sand to make mortar or with water, sand and aggregate to make concrete."}
{"id": "88089372-1609-4aad-9853-a71026d556cc", "value": "Composed of sand, stones or other aggregate and cement mixed with water which sets in a hard mass."}

{"id": "5470e902-5a6f-4e76-ad27-382eae046940", "value": "Granular material consisting of small eroded fragments of rock or mineral grains, finer than gravel used as an ingredient in mortar and other traditional building materials."}
{"id": "adba59a5-4913-4def-a03b-89a6c59847bf", "value": "A mixture of lime or more recently cement with sand and water used for bonding stones or bricks."}
{"id": "9874056a-220a-4f7c-bb07-85aeee018982", "value": "A binder combined with various aggregates which sets and holds together into a mass which then hardens and gains strength."}
{"id": "95b29bd3-234d-49d5-a25d-e175690ea0d9", "value": "Transparent, hard substance made by fusing soda-silica which solidifies from a molten state."}

{"id": "8a401ad3-8d89-485c-bdf1-66e9e44a77ab", "value": "A material or combination of materials manufactured by human effort, or fashioned into shape by man or a man made industrial process (excluding metal). See MAN MADE MATERIAL Class List for narrow terms."}
{"id": "49f7531f-0e60-41fd-9847-4c3de10cc36b", "value": "By-product or waste, resulting from an industrial process."}
{"id": "a0f009d2-ee64-48c9-9c71-1b5b1a687b2f", "value": "Durable wood from a non-native, evergreen conifer."}

{"id": "a816d208-a966-43fd-9268-6e53a6be3b54", "value": "Part-decomposed vegetable matter formed under waterlogged conditions into a firm, brown deposit resembling soil. Used as a brick for infilling in timber framed walls."}
{"id": "dc15a237-edd9-4585-9784-055f86cd5622", "value": "Wood of a coniferous tree."}

{"id": "6cf4e364-9c3d-4ca1-849b-f88061967ba4", "value": "Walls composed of clay, earth, straw, lime and sand, mixed with water. Constructed without shutters in layers upon a stone or brick plinth and usually covered with protective limewash."}
{"id": "fa5750f4-0bd8-4012-aa4f-0110c0773bdb", "value": "Ground-covering herbage, some varieties of which can be used, especially when dried and in large quantities, as a construction material."}

{"id": "9f456a24-2924-47cb-9e2a-97b312e039fc", "value": "Roofing material consisting of stems or stalks of wheat, rye, oats or barley separated from grain and laid flat in 'yealms' which form an overlapping surface which sheds water."}

{"id": "1fa79a6b-3915-40e3-a0c4-8491e6c06bf2", "value": "A dwarf shrub of the heath family used as an alternative to straw as a roof covering in moorland regions. Cut while in bloom and laid with the roots carefully entwined. The covering turns a characteristic black colour with age."}
{"id": "16a0429a-b21c-4e53-a3b6-1f3eeb5d6fd1", "value": "Any tree, shrub or herb of cellulose form, normally subsisting in soil and producing its food through photosynthesis."}
{"id": "36d24a18-a86a-4fad-928b-9a99fc5f5370", "value": "Multicellular marine alga, which grows on the seashore, in salt marshes, in brackish water or submerged in the ocean."}

{"id": "3f6ce180-4ce2-4f3f-9a8e-544620893719", "value": "The tall, straight stalks or stems formed by plants found in the wetland areas, particularly The Fens. Used as a roofing material, the reed is laid with the ends forming the exposed covering surface."}

{"id": "9532291b-82e0-4e2e-ac03-9b79e051981e", "value": "Combination of organic and inorganic material cohered to form a hard solid wall or covering. Use for structures created by the excavation and piling up of earth, such as ice houses. Earth may be used in combination with other materials."}
{"id": "12dc61f0-4b33-42aa-a6a9-37a6f00bd405", "value": "Unbaked clays and/or soil material often mixed with, or performing the function of an aggregate or binder."}

{"id": "26b192c9-0cfc-434e-ad4b-611586e9f17a", "value": "Wet soil, sand or other earthy matter combined with ballast and bonded with straw or other binding material. Walls are built in the absence of shuttering by the simple process of pitching in layers."}
{"id": "8989f94a-a397-4128-9128-fa983438a4de", "value": "Rammed earth or clay of a low moisture content used to make floors or walls, or found between shuttering."}
{"id": "ad37ca4f-3d75-46ec-96fd-754dacd88d01", "value": "An unconsolidated geological deposit sometimes iused as a bonding material in stone walls."}
{"id": "659c9ef1-8b39-4c4a-8514-9ca7a6f6b779", "value": "Hard, protective covering made largely of calcium salts secreted by soft bodied invertebrate animals."}
{"id": "1a75dfa1-8f5f-46c4-b1f6-aa0334e9fa78", "value": "Waste material or dross separated from metals during smelting or refining."}
{"id": "eca61488-8948-4a0d-8a2e-94012c35be87", "value": "Tropical giant grass with hollow stem used structurally or as a covering material."}
{"id": "36dcd69b-e5ea-4f3f-ae0a-7c76ef870702", "value": "Fused ash from furnaces used as aggregate."}
{"id": "0d8e3bf5-a050-4823-82ca-ce65c8b770cb", "value": "A woven or bonded fabric or cloth."}
{"id": "96ba5df8-f124-4b8f-831d-846baceaae1c", "value": "Buoyant, light material obtained from the cork tree."}
{"id": "c820d84a-30c5-45b2-bccc-6cc2197d9a67", "value": "Pertaining to or deriving from a living organism. See ANIMAL Class list for narrow terms."}

{"id": "c60788ba-a8b2-4e3d-a478-db851d32ef1a", "value": "Hard, durable, dark grey stone, the purest native form of silica, which can either be used decoratively or as a main material. Predominantly found in East Anglia and the South East."}
{"id": "22c9ca12-cfe9-4ef3-8235-b94527fe4d41", "value": "Layer of grass with earth and matted roots cut from the ground and used for earth buildings and as a covering material."}
{"id": "6fe96471-e993-48ba-93bc-3109f22b75c4", "value": "Dating from the 15th century, it is a hard alloy of iron and carbon, melted and shaped into various moulded forms."}
{"id": "e2d0609d-4669-4012-9ddf-a897c21bada0", "value": "Pertaining to or deriving from a botanical living organism. See VEGETAL Class List for narrow terms."}
